description.value:
Papyrus written with black ink with demotic text on recto and verso.
Thompson's MS Catalogue: "Mounted in eleven unnumbered frames. Provenance ? Writing. various hands and periods. several columns on both recto & verso. Contents. Frame (A). recto 5 cols. & vestiges of a previous one. a land register. verso. 21 cols. prob. a summing up of the totals of aruras on the recto. Frame (B). recto. 9 cols. list of inhabitants of houses(?). verso. 9 cols. (rougher hand). list mainly of parts of the body - often repeated. [...] list of a butcher - possibly distribution to temple officials of sacrificial animals. Frame (C). recto. 5 cols. arithmetical problems. Frame (E). recto 7 cols. list of names. cols. 1 & 2 [...] male - the rest appar. female. verso. 5 cols. accounts. Frame (F). recto 5 fragments, joined but not belonging (two mounted upside down). fragt. no. 2 - part of land register headed "The island of Pnesh year 21". etc. Date. early Roman(?). Origin. perhaps Memphis".

description.value:
Papyrus written with black ink with demotic literary text (wisdom text with narrative frame): the Instructions of 'Onchsheshonqy.
Thompson's MS Catalogue: "mounted in ten frames. [...] The roll has lost its beginning (there are vestiges of a column preceding the first) and its end. It is all written in one hand. Contents. The first eight frames containing 26 columns consist of a collection of proverbs & moral sayings. Frames IX+X containing 4 columns and 9 fragments consist of portions of a historical romance, in which one Anch-Sheshanqy son of Djainofre(?) (cf. Spiegelberg, Petubastis Sage. p. 79 no. 31) seems to play a principal part."

description.value: Book of the Dead of Ankhwahibra (sheet 18): the vignette shows the judgment hall. The roof is supported by columns, and Osiris sits enthroned as judge, under a canopy. Before him are the forty-two assessors in two rows, probably intended to be seated along the walls of the hall. The dead man appears twice, adoring each group. The main action of the scene is the weighing of the heart. Anubis and Horus tend the balance, while Thoth with his scribal palette and pen records the outcome. It is favourable to Ankhwahibra for he appears with arms upraised in jubilation, supported by Maat, the goddess who personified the concept of Right and Order. The Devourer Ammit, once again cheated of her prey, sits on a pedestal facing Osiris.
